9. Inter jurisperitos disceptatum est utrum maria et oceanus dominio alicujus subjacere possint. Satis jam exploratum videtur partes maris continenti adjectas, itemque sinus et freta occupari posse, et dominio gentis alicujus subjici, quum ob piscationem, patriae defensionem, et commercii securitatem id expediat. Oceanus vero et maria magna nullius subjacent dominic, quum nequeant ab ulla gente occupari, et usus sint inexhausti, quo scilicet universi, absque singulorum detrimento, frui possint.²

Kentius dicit: “ Navigable rivers which flow through a territory, and the sea coast adjoining it, and the navigable waters included in bays, and between headlands and arms of the sea, belong to the sovereign of the adjoining territory, as being necessary to the safety of the natinn, and to the undisturbed use of the neighbouring shores. The open sea is not capable of being possessed as private property. The free use of the ocean - for navigation and fishing, is common to all mankind, and the public jurists gene rally and explicitly deny that the main ocean can ever be appropriated.” Kent’s Comm. vol. i. p. i. lec. i. n. 26.
